NNAAMMEE
       ssttrroonnggooppss - Register with StrongOps

       The  "strongops"  command  registers users with the StrongOps platform.
       The simplest usage is ssllcc ssttrroonnggooppss. The command prompts for user name,
       email  and  a  password  and  then  saves  the  credentials to ./stron-
       gloop.json. If no command line options are given for name or email, the
       strongops  command  tries  to find defaults from ~~//..ggiittccoonnffiigg (name and
       email) and then ~~//..nnppmmrrcc  (email).  However,  when  you  specify  valid
       options  on  the command line, there are no interactive prompts for the
       data specified on the command line.

SSYYNNOOPPSSIISS
       slc strongops [options]

OOPPTTIIOONNSS
       +o   ----nnaammee: Specify the full user  name,  e.g.:  ----nnaammee  ''BBoobb  RRoobbeerrttss''
           (quotes are needed as the full name contains a space).

       +o   ----eemmaaiill:  Specify  the  email address, e.g.: ----eemmaaiill ssoommeeoonnee@@ssttrroonn--
           gglloooopp..ccoomm.

       +o   ----ppaasssswwoorrdd:  Specify  your  StrongOps  password,  e.g.:  ----ppaasssswwoorrdd
           1122334455667788

       +o   ----nnoossaavvee:  Prevent  saving  of  StrongOps account credentials, this
           overrides any save option.

       +o   ----llooccaall: Saves StrongOps account credentials in a ..//ssttrroonngglloooopp..jjssoonn
           file. This is set by default, if no other save options exist.

       +o   ----ppaacckkaaggee:  Saves  StrongOps  account credentials in ..//ppaacckkaaggee..jjssoonn
           file, if the file exists.

       +o   ----gglloobbaall:  Saves  StrongOps  account  credentials  in  a   ~~//ssttrroonn--
           gglloooopp..jjssoonn file.

       +o   ----rreeggiisstteerr:  Skips  attempt  to  login and registers a new user. By
           default, the command logs users into StrongOps.

       +o   ----ssaavveeaallll:  Saves  StrongOps  account   credentials   to   ..//ssttrroonn--
           gglloooopp..jjssoonn, ..//ppaacckkaaggee..jjssoonn and ~~//ssttrroonngglloooopp..jjssoonn files.

       +o   ----nnooccoolloorrss: Does not use ANSI colors in the responses - this is the
           default.

       +o   ----ccoolloorrss: Use ANSI  colors.  If  used  with  ----nnooccoolloorrss,  overrides
           ----nnooccoolloorrss.

       See  strong-agent _h_t_t_p_:_/_/_d_o_c_s_._s_t_r_o_n_g_o_p_s_._c_o_m_/_s_t_r_o_n_g_-_a_g_e_n_t for a descrip-
       tion of the format of the ppaacckkaaggee..jjssoonn and  ssttrroonngglloooopp..jjssoonn  properties
       used by Strong Ops.

EEXXAAMMPPLLEESS
       The  following will have strongops prompt for the name, email and pass-
       word. The JSON containing the strongops credentials are sent  to  stan-
       dard output:

               $ slc strongops

       Next,  the  strongops credentials are saved to the local ..//ppaacckkaaggee..jjssoonn
       file:

               $ slc strongops --package

       By using the options for name, email  and  password,  you  can  have  a
       non-interactive registration, e.g. that will not prompt:

               $ slc strongops --name "Bill Williams" --email "bw@strongops.com" --password "12345678"

       Using  the  saveall  option causes strongops to save the credentials to
       ..//ppaacckkaaggee..jjssoonn, ..//ssttrroonngglloooopp..jjssoonn and ~~//ssttrroonngglloooopp..jjssoonn:

               $ slc strongops --saveall

       Applications can be set up so that whether Strong Ops profiling  occurs
       is configured at deploy/run time, based on whether the credentials have
       been saved. To do this, call pprrooffiillee(()) with no arguments, as below:

               // app.js
               // Call profile() before any modules which need profiling are
               // required. In the absence of credentials, this is effectively
               // a null op.
               require('strong-agent').profile();

               // ... rest of application is required ...

